\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The first evaluator presented a fairly negative report on the programme recommending that it should not be accredited. The second evaluator\'27s report is more positive\'2C but the concerns raised in terms of Criterion 1 suggest that the original evaluator recommendation should be upheld.\line Although the second evaluator indicated that the \'E2\'80\'9Ccoursework\'E2\'80\'9D M.A. application for accreditation in International Relations does reflect the required academic depth in terms of the courses it offers and the mini -dissertation component of the degree\'2C the differentiation between the Master\'27s and Honours degrees is not sufficiently clear. This problem appears to be a result of the fact that there really is no delineation of the differences of courses offered at the M.A. and Honours levels except for two to three modules. The M.A. programme appears to be a carbon copy of the intended rationale for Honours students in preparing students for the workplace\'2C indicating that\'2C as an example\'2C graduates would be prepared \'E2\'80\'9C... to slot into national diplomatic missions to meet significant shortages of well-trained diplomatic personnel.\'E2\'80\'9D There is no clarity how the values of the two degrees differ in practice as they seem to be targeting the same level of preparedness for both Honours and M.A. students on graduation. The proposed Master\'E2\'80\'99s degree is lacking in clarity with respect to the learning activities component.The evaluator felt that lectures at a Master\'27s degree level are not appropriate and that it should be seminar_based. In addition\'2C the programme does not sufficiently satisfy the institution\'27s model of aspiring to an \'E2\'80\'9CAfrican vision\'E2\'80\'9D given that the courses offered for both the MA and Honours do not give sufficient attention to International Relations study pertaining to the continent. This is a discrepancy that should be addressed to make sure that there is indeed a bias towards the stated mission of the institution.\line The evaluator also indicated that Criterion 2 does not satisfactorily address the Recognition of Prior Learning criterion. It is not clearly specified what sort of prior work experience prospective candidates should have and what their assessment portfolio would entail. This raises the concern that it might well be that the programme has almost the same requirements for students entering both degree programmes which would not be satisfactory.\line \line \cell \pard 

